{
  "buggy_files": ["fs/nfs/dir.c", "net/sunrpc/sched.c"],
  "buggy_functions": ["nfs_lookup_revalidate", "rpc_wait_bit_killable"],
  "confidence": 0.82,
  "reasoning": "The bug manifests in two locations: (1) Primary: fs/nfs/dir.c in nfs_lookup_revalidate (lines 1158-1162). When nfs_lookup_verify_inode() returns a negative error such as -ERESTARTSYS (-512), the code unconditionally jumps to out_zap_parent -> out_bad which returns 0 (dentry invalid). This causes the VFS to call d_invalidate() on the /storage dentry, unmounting the autofs mount. The fix should check whether the error is negative (a real error) and propagate it via the out_error label instead, so the dentry is NOT invalidated. The debug message 'NFS: nfs_lookup_revalidate(/storage) is invalid' at the out_bad label (returning 0) confirms this path. (2) Secondary: net/sunrpc/sched.c in rpc_wait_bit_killable. This function returns -ERESTARTSYS when fatal_signal_pending(current) is true, even before attempting to schedule. During autofs expiry/unmount, a fatal signal (SIGKILL) can be pending for the process performing the NFS getattr. The function immediately returns -ERESTARTSYS without waiting for the reply, which tcpdump confirms arrives later. The regression from 3.14.12 to 4.1.15 is caused by nfs_lookup_revalidate treating all non-zero returns from nfs_lookup_verify_inode as 'dentry invalid' rather than propagating actual error codes. When -ERESTARTSYS propagates from rpc_wait_bit_killable -> rpc_call_sync -> nfs_proc_getattr -> __nfs_revalidate_inode -> nfs_lookup_verify_inode -> nfs_lookup_revalidate, the last function incorrectly invalidates the /storage dentry instead of returning the error to the VFS."
}

